180. In Corum alque Eurum] Corus (or Caurus) is the N.W. wind, as Eurus is the S.E. He flogged whatever wind op- posed him. This may be a playful inven- tion of J uvenal's, making Xerxes a hai-der master to the winds than Aeolus himself, and he was stern enough according to Virgil. Xerxes' castigation and chaining of the Hellespont for breaking down his bridge are told by Aeschylus (Persae v. 745, sqq.) and Herodotus (vii. 35). The truth of the story is not admitted by the latest editors of those authors, Paley and Blakesley, and others before them.
